  "text": "Indeed, recent data indicate that cannabinoids directly modulate GlyR. The nature of this modulation depends on concentration of glycine. At low doses of the glycine (<EC 30 ), cannabinoids augment GlyR-induced currents (I Gly ), while suppress at high concentrations of glycine (>EC 50 ; [CITATION_1] Hejazi et al., 2006; [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Thus cannabinoids exert dual concentration-dependent effects on I Gly .",
